Ford GoBike System Data Analysis¶

by Jimmy Ogeto¶

Introduction¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in the Ford GoBike system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area between 2019-02-01 and 2019-02-28.

Quality issues¶

  • member_birth_year, start_time and end_time coulmns have wrong data types
  • start-station_id, start_station_name, end_station_id, end_station_name, member_birth_year, member_gender have missing values

Feature engineering¶

  • create a day, month, start_hour columns from the start_time columns
  • create a time_of_day(TOD) column
  • creates a duration_minutes column
  • create an age and age_group column fom the member_birth_year column
In [17]:
# creating a day, month, start_hour columns
bikes_clean['week'] = bikes_clean['start_time'].dt.isocalendar().week
bikes_clean['day'] = bikes_clean['start_time'].dt.day_name().str[:3]
bikes_clean['hour'] = bikes_clean['start_time'].dt.hour

In [19]:
# creating a TOD-time_of_day
labels = ['early_morning', 'morning', 'afternoon', 'night']
bins = [0, 6, 12, 19, 23]
bikes_clean['TOD'] = pd.cut(bikes_clean['hour'], bins=bins, labels=labels, include_lowest=True)
In [20]:
# creating a duration_minutes column
bikes_clean['duration_minutes'] = np.rint(bikes_clean['duration_sec']/60)
In [21]:
# making the day and TOD columns ordered
ordered_cats = {'day':['Mon', 'Tue', 'Wed', 'Thu', 'Fri', 'Sat','Sun'],
                'TOD':['early_morning', 'morning', 'afternoon', 'night']}
for col in ordered_cats:
    cat_ordered = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True, categories=ordered_cats[col])
    bikes_clean[col] = bikes_clean[col].astype(cat_ordered)
In [22]:
# creating an age column
bikes_clean['age'] = 2019 - bikes_clean['member_birth_year']

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

  • After cleaning and adding new columns through feature engineering, this dataset has 174,952 rows and 22 columns.
  • Initially there were 16 columns but through feature engineering, 6 more columns were created.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

There is no one feature of interest as I'm looking at the interactions between some of the features of the dataset to find out how they relate to each other.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The duration_minutes, hour, week, TOD, age, day, member_gender, user_type are features that are of interest.

  • The duration_minutes column has a largely long tailed distribution with a majority of the bike rides lasting between 1 and 40 minutes. In a logscale distribution,it can be seen that the distribution is slightly bimodal with a the first peak between 3-5 minutes and the other between 10 and 15 minutes.

  • Next we look at how bike rides are distributed across time of the day.

Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

  • Yes, I needed to create some new features to ake analysis of the data easier. From sthe start_time column I extracted the hour, day, month, TOD columns. I also made a duration in minutes column and created an age and age_group column from the member_birth_year column.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

  • Because of the few large outliers in the duration_minute column which aused a long tailed distribution, had touse a log scale distribution and zoom in on values <100 minutes. It was also very interesting to find that a mojority of the bike riders only ride the bike for less than 40 minutes.

  • In the hour column, ther 2 peaks at 8am and 5pm. Also, there was a significant amount of bike riders one hour befor and one hour after the 2 peaks.

  • Another interesting distribution was that of the day column, where the weekdays recorded the highest number of riders while the number of riders on the weekend was considerable low in comparison.
